 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/udaesetyoo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Daese TYoo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/10/02 5:58:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22695.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> <br>
The one thing I will say about rogue that is negative is this- there really isn't much you can do to truly shine.  As a caster, you have the opportunity to impress people a whole lot.  I'll log my shaman on and STILL get tells almost immediately, even though I haven't played him in about 6 months.  <br>
<br>
I switched to rogue cause the shaman was too high demand too much work, and I wanted loot!  Now my rogue is my higher character, and I've loved him most of the way, but now being in a larger guild its tough, cause I'm &quot;just another rogue.&quot;  I've done what I can to stand apart- I've got 230ish poison skill, I'm always the one volunteering to pick, and always the one dying cause monks CR better than rogues when you have too many see-hide wanderers (thanks new CT).<br>
<br>
All in all, I like being a rogue, but sometimes its hard to stay distinct- I know which enchanter is always fast on the snake, I can tell you which cleric bitches if I ask for aego in a tell, but to the guild (which is where it really matters) I'm just another rogue.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uguythebastard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Guythebastard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/10/02 7:45:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22695.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> I have a rogue and a cleric in the low 50's. I personally identify more with my rogue, and tend to play my cleric when group/ raid balance requires a healer.  <br>
<br>
There are also occasional times (esp at 3am when doing the xp grind thing) that sitting down, and popping up to heal/ stun etc can be relatively relaxing. You certainly have to be more actively engaged when playing a melee most of the time, esp as a rogue where you're having to constantly reposition yourself to keep the back shreading going.<br>
<br>
There's also the usual dynamic around finding groups - while rogue's and their damage output are greatly more understood at highish lvls, clerics will still spend a lot less time marketing their services, and will get invites to groups/ raids where they are up to 5 levels light.<br>
<br>
So for me; I love my rogue - very complex, engaging class. For ease of play though, Clr probably has the edge. <p><P><select>
